## Analysis

I worked through this carefully. The house-style items (`@doc`/`@spec`, line length, markers) are all satisfied, and standard Elixir finds no unused variables, unreachable clauses, or deprecations in `solution.ex`. That points at Elixir 1.18+'s **type checker**, which flags `nil`-related mismatches at compile time.

The culprit is in `test_harness.exs`, appearing **exactly twice**:

```elixir
params = URI.decode_query(URI.parse(uri).query)
```

`URI.parse/1` returns a `%URI{}` whose `:query` field is typed `nil | binary()`, but `URI.decode_query/1` expects a `binary()`. Passing a possibly-`nil` value yields a type warning — once per occurrence = **2 warnings**.

Note that `solution.ex`'s own `parse_uri/1` already guards this with `URI.decode_query(query || "")`, which is why the solution compiles clean while the harness does not. The fix is to apply the same `|| ""` guard in the two test sites. This changes no behavior (the URI always carries a query, so the fallback never triggers) and weakens no assertion.

